                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-276-off1519 t18290910-276-victim2594"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-276-person2595">
                  THOMAS 
                  SPOONER ROWSELL
               <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2595" type="surname" value="SPOONER ROWSELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2595" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2595" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was opposite the <placeName id="t18290910-276-crimeloc1521">Mansion-house</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-276-crimeloc1521" type="placeName" value="Mansion-house"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-276-crimeloc1521" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-276-off1519 t18290910-276-crimeloc1521"></join>, on the 28th of July, about a quarter before three o'clock - I heard some one call, "Sir, you are robbed;" I missed my handkerchief, and saw it on the ground - I had had it not ten minutes before; this is it: I saw White and Wood in custody when I turned round; Jeffries had one and Breakwell another - I did not see Wells.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-276-person2596">
                  GEORGE 
                  JEFFRIES
               <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2596" type="surname" value="JEFFRIES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2596" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2596" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 28th of July, I took hold of Wood, a little before three o'clock, having suspicion that he was picking pockets - I did not see him do any thing, but I had seen him for about an hour in company with the other two, passing up and down Ludgate-hill; I saw the prosecutor's handkerchief on the ground, just before he was aware he had lost it; I did not see it fall, but it was nearest to White - Wood was close to him, and Wells within one yard.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. Were there many other persons there? A. Yes; I did not see Wells do any thing - they were altogether; I had before seen White attempt to pick a gentleman's pocket, and at that time Wells was about a yard and a half from him; I am a solicitor - I do not usually walk about the street; I had not seen Wells till within that hour, but I can swear he was one of them.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-276-person2597">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BREAKWELL
               <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2597" type="surname" value="BREAKWELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2597" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2597" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a carrier. I saw the prisoners together by the Old Jewry - they walked towards the Mansion-house; I saw White take the handkerchief from this gentleman's pocket; I got out of my cart, and caught hold of him - he threw the handkerchief down; the other two were within a few yards of him - Wood was within a yard and a half of him, and Wells within four or five yards - Mr. Jeffries took hold of Wood - he then went into the Poultry, and took Wells.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. How many persons were passing? A. Several; White was not twenty yards from the other two - there might be six or seven people between them when I saw White on one side of the road; Wells and Wood ran across to try to draw him away by whistling and beckoning, but he would not come - White was then following the prosecutor, but the robbery had not then been committed.</p>
               <p>MR. LEE to MR. JEFFRIES. Q. What time did you see them on Ludgate-hill? A. About two o'clock - I looked at St. Paul's clock; I think it was not past two - it could not be more than half-past two.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Did it appear to you that they were within a yard and a half of White? A. It appeared so.</p>
               <p>Prisoner White. Q. Was there not a boy with me who told you where the handkerchief laid? A. No; I did not pick it up - there might be two persons between Wood and the boy.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-276-person2598">
                  DANIEL 
                  FORRESTER
               <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2598" type="surname" value="FORRESTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2598" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-person2598" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I received them in custody.</p>

               <p>White's Defence. I was coming by the Mansion-house with another boy; the witness said I had picked the gentleman's pocket, and the boy with me told where the handkerchief laid.</p>
               <p>WHITE - <rs id="t18290910-276-verdict1522" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290910-276-verdict1522" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 15.</p>
